<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eriogonum arborescens </i>is a rounded shrub that produces clusters of many crowded, frilly flowers that are white to rosy on nearly naked flowering stalks. Plants occur on Santa Rosa, Santa Cruz, and Anacapa Islands. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum grande </i>is a mat-forming plant producing tall, stout clusters of white, pink or red flowers. <i>E. grande </i>involves var. <i>grande </i>(a CNPS list 4.2 plant) found on San Miguel, Santa Cruz,  Anacapa, Santa Catalina, and San Clemente islands; var. <i>rubescens </i>(a CNPS list 1B.2 plant) found on San Miguel, Santa Rosa, and Santa Cruz Islands; and var. <i>timorum </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) found on San Nicolas Island. <br/>
<br/>
Both buckwheat species occur together and separately on dry, rocky slopes, bluffs, and stabilized dunes in associations with other coastal shrubs, subshrubs, and various annual herbs along the northern Channel Islands. Stands also can include rare species, including <i>Castilleja hololeuca </i>(a CNPS list 1B.2 plant) and various rare <i>Dudleya </i>spp., and they are usually are invaded by non-native grasses. Junak et al. (2007) summarized survey data collected by Johnson and Rodriguez (2001), and Rodriguez et al. (2017) summarized data across the northern Channel Islands. They noted <i>E. arborescens</i> stands on Santa Cruz and Anacapa Islands, <i>E. grande </i>var. <i>grande </i> stands on Santa Cruz Island, and var. <i>rubescens </i>stands on San Miguel and Santa Rosa Island. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
