    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bh). Stands are mapped on Santa Cruz Island (AIS 2007c), and have been sampled and mapped on Santa Rosa, San Miguel, Santa Cruz and Anacapa Island (Rodriguez et al. 2017) including <i>Eriogonum arborescens, E. grande </i>var. <i>grande </i>and <i>E. grande </i>var. <i>rubescens</i>. Stands of <i>E. grande </i>var. <i>timorum </i>are present on San Nicolas Island which are similar in composition to <i>E. grande </i>var. <i>rubescens</i> stands (HDR 2014b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Goats, sheep, cattle, and rabbits grazed heavily on native vegetation in the Channel Islands, which had previously restricted shrubland vegetation and increased non-native grassland invasion. Now that grazers have been removed, some shrub species including the endemic buckwheats appear to be expanding in cover and extent, though recovery of native plants is varied (Beltran et al. 2014, Corry 2006, Van Vuren 2014, Yelenik and Levine 2010). In particular, <i>Eriogonum arborescens </i> and <i>Artemisia californica</i>, two species considered vulnerable to grazing (Coblentz 1978, Brumbaugh 1980, Minnich 1980a), have been shown to increase variably in abundance on Santa Cruz Island after removal from sheep grazing (Van Vuren 2014); however, factors that can limit their recovery include competition from non-native annual grasses and lack of water availability in low rainfall years (Yelenik and Levine 2010). Another factor limiting native shrub recovery has been the invasion of fennel, <i>Foeniculum vulgare</i>, and other non-native herbs upon removal of grazers (Zavaleta et al. 2001); restoration efforts on Santa Cruz Island have included removal of fennel and reseeding of native shrubs (Power et al. 2014). </div>
</div>

    

    

